0.009274043142795563, -0.03368206322193146, 0.011404275894165039, -0.004296327941119671, -0.02850351668894291, 0.02628004178404808, 0.008033200167119503, 0.02009734697639942, -0.01763000711798668, 0.01018495112657547, 0.01292484626173973, -0.014000721275806427, 0.038444604724645615, -0.011016961187124252, -0.006171936634927988, 0.001677468535490334, -0.03936268389225006, -0.011483173817396164, -0.014947490766644478, -0.00989805068820715, -0.014352173544466496, -0.020871976390480995, 0.013053950853645802, -0.028374413028359413, -0.021603571251034737, 0.01788821630179882, -0.006828220561146736, -0.00378708029165864, -0.011181928217411041, -0.005232339259237051]], "input": ["\"MOTIVATION IN BUDGETING\":\"The budgeting system can influence the behaviour of managers and employees, and may motivate them to improve their performance if the target represented by the budget is set at an appropriate level. An inappropriate target has the potential to be de-motivating, however, and a key factor here is the degree of participation in the budget-setting process. It has been shown that an appropriate degree of participation can have a positive motivational effect.\"", "\"PERFORMANCE EVALUATION IN BUDGETING\":\"Managerial performance is often evaluated by the extent to which budgetary targets for which individual managers are responsible have been achieved. Managerial rewards such as bonuses or performance-related pay can also be linked to achievement of budgetary targets. Managers can also use the budget to evaluate their own performance and clarify how close they are to meeting agreed performance targets.\"", "\"SALES VOLUME AND VARIANCE ANALYSIS FOR MILBAO CO\":\"Milbao Co makes and sells three types of electronic game for which the following budget/standard information and actual information is available for a four-week period: Model: Superb, Excellent, Good; Budget sales (units): 30,000, 50,000, 20,000; Standard unit data Selling price ($): 100, 80, 70; Variable cost ($): 40, 25, 22; Actual sales (units): 36,000, 42,000, 18,000; Budgeted fixed costs are $2,500,000 for the four-week period.\"", "\"CONTRIBUTION BASIS\":\"Contribution basis for sales volume variance is calculated as the difference between actual and budgeted sales units multiplied by the contribution per unit.\"", "\"NET PROFIT BASIS\":\"Net profit basis for sales volume variance is calculated as the difference between actual and budgeted sales units multiplied by the profit per unit.\"", "\"MATERIAL AND LABOUR VARIANCE ANALYSIS FOR PAN-OCEAN CHEMICALS\":\"Pan-Ocean Chemicals produces Synthon using three types of materials and labor. The case involves calculating material mix, yield, and usage variances, as well as labor rate and efficiency variances, based on standard and actual costs and quantities.\"", "\"REVISED STANDARD COST OF ACTUAL OUTPUT\":\"Revised standard cost of actual output (122,000 units * 1.4 hours * $13 per hour) = $2,220,400\"", "\"OPERATING VARIANCE\":\"Operating variance is the difference between the revised standard cost and the actual cost. In this case, it is $222,040 (F).\"", "\"ACTUAL LABOUR COST\":\"Actual labour cost = $1,998,360\"", "\"LABOUR USAGE PLANNING VARIANCE\":\"Labour usage planning variance is calculated as the difference between the actual output at original standard time per unit and the actual output at revised standard time per unit, both multiplied by the original standard rate. In this case, it is $219,600 (A).\"", "\"LABOUR PRICE PLANNING VARIANCE\":\"Labour price planning variance is calculated as the difference between the actual output at revised standard time per unit at original standard rate and the actual output at revised standard time per unit at revised standard rate. In this case, it is $170,800 (A).\"", "\"PRINCIPLES OF REVISING STANDARDS\":\"Principles of revising standards involve ensuring that managers are judged only on factors they can control. Standards should be revised for uncontrollable factors before variance analysis is performed to reflect accurate performance. Revisions should be authorized by a senior, independent body to ensure fairness.\"", "\"FACTORS FOR VARIANCE INVESTIGATION\":\"Factors to consider in deciding whether a variance should be investigated include the size of the variance, whether it is adverse or favorable, cost versus benefits of investigation, historic pattern of variances, and the reliability and quality of data.\"", "\"BUDGET REVISIONS AND SALES VARIANCE ANALYSIS FOR SPIKE CO\":\"Spike Co manufactures and sells good quality leather bound diaries. The company budgets for its profits, including detailed budgets for sales, materials, and labour. The managing director is concerned about the frequency of budget revisions, which seem to result in favourable operational variance reports but less profit than promised. The case discusses circumstances for allowing or refusing budget revisions, specific situations for materials and labour budget revisions, and sales performance analysis.\"", "\"SALES VARIANCE ANALYSIS\":\"Sales variance analysis involves calculating the total sales price and total sales volume variance, as well as market size and market share variances, to assess the sales performance of a business.\"", "\"MATERIALS BUDGET REVISION\":\"A local material supplier was forced into liquidation, and a new supplier 150 miles away charged more for the material and delivery. A budget revision is sought for the two months where higher prices had to be paid.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}